0megaSkyeGate — DEPLOY GUIDE (Plain English Version)
Written for: someone who has never deployed a Cloudflare Worker before
Source platform: Skye0s-s0l26/Sky0s-Platforms/0megaSkyeGate/0megaSkyeGate-The-Actual-Gate/
================================================================================

WHAT ARE WE DEPLOYING?
================================================================================
0megaSkyeGate is a Cloudflare Worker — basically a small server that runs at
Cloudflare's edge, all around the world, with no actual server you manage.
It acts as the single front door for ALL AI calls across every Skye platform.
Instead of every app talking directly to OpenAI, Gemini, or Anthropic, they
all talk to THIS worker, and it figures out which AI provider to use, tracks
spending (in SKYFUEL), and logs everything.

This guide is the source of truth for the AI gateway layer only.
Legacy client database/auth stacks are not part of a valid 0megaSkyeGate deployment.
Do not add legacy client config values or provider keys to downstream
browser apps when wiring AI. Provider keys live on 0megaSkyeGate only.

Live URL once deployed:
  https://0megaskyegate.skyesoverlondon.workers.dev


DOWNSTREAM PLATFORM RULES
================================================================================
If a platform needs AI, it must route through 0megaSkyeGate.

Valid downstream AI env patterns in this repo are:

  - Browser / static apps:
      OMEGA_GATE_URL=https://0megaskyegate.skyesoverlondon.workers.dev
      The browser may also read window.OMEGA_GATE_URL or localStorage OMEGA_GATE_URL.

  - Netlify / server-side apps:
      OMEGA_GATE_URL=https://0megaskyegate.skyesoverlondon.workers.dev
      KAIXU_APP_TOKEN=issued-from-0megaSkyeGate-admin-api

  - SuperIDE server-side alias:
      KAIXU_GATEWAY_ENDPOINT=https://0megaskyegate.skyesoverlondon.workers.dev
      KAIXU_APP_TOKEN=issued-from-0megaSkyeGate-admin-api

What does NOT belong in downstream AI wiring:

  - OpenAI_API_KEY, GEMINI_API_KEY, ANTHROPIC_API_KEY on browser apps
  - Legacy client-database config values for AI routing
  - Direct browser-side persistence config for AI routing

If a platform still has a legacy direct browser persistence stack in its codebase, treat that as
legacy technical debt to remove. It is not part of the approved AI env model.


BEFORE YOU START — WHAT YOU NEED
================================================================================

1. A Cloudflare account
   Go to dash.cloudflare.com and log in (or create one — it's free to start).

2. Wrangler CLI installed
   This is the command-line tool that deploys to Cloudflare.
   Run this once if you don't have it:
     npm install -g wrangler

3. You need to log Wrangler into your Cloudflare account:
     wrangler login
   A browser window will open. Click "Allow". Done.

4. API keys from the AI providers you want to use:
   - OpenAI  → platform.openai.com → API Keys
   - Gemini  → aistudio.google.com → API Keys
   - Anthropic → console.anthropic.com → API Keys
   You don't need all three — just the ones you're activating.

5. Node.js installed (v18 or newer)
   Check with: node --version
   If you don't have it: nodejs.org


STEP 1 — GO INTO THE PROJECT FOLDER
================================================================================

Open your terminal and navigate to the gate folder:

  cd Skye0s-s0l26/Sky0s-Platforms/0megaSkyeGate/0megaSkyeGate-The-Actual-Gate

Install dependencies (only needed first time):

  npm install

That's it for setup. The project has no complex build pipeline — Wrangler handles
everything else.


STEP 2 — CREATE YOUR SECRETS FILE (local development only)
================================================================================

There is a file called .dev.vars.example in the folder. This is the template
for your secret keys. You need to copy it and fill it in.

  cp .dev.vars.example .dev.vars

Now open .dev.vars and fill in your values. Here is what each section means:

── OPENAI KEYS ──
  OPENAI_API_KEY      = your main OpenAI key (goes into all OpenAI calls)
  OPENAI_TEXT_KEY     = can be the same as OPENAI_API_KEY
  OPENAI_IMAGES_KEY   = can be the same as OPENAI_API_KEY
  OPENAI_VIDEOS_KEY   = can be the same as OPENAI_API_KEY (Sora key if separate)
  OPENAI_AUDIO_KEY    = can be the same as OPENAI_API_KEY
  OPENAI_REALTIME_KEY = can be the same as OPENAI_API_KEY
  OPENAI_PROJECT_ID   = your OpenAI Project ID (found in platform.openai.com)

   TIP: If you only have one OpenAI key, paste it into all six KEY fields.

── OTHER PROVIDER KEYS ──
  GEMINI_API_KEY    = your Google Gemini API key
  ANTHROPIC_API_KEY = your Anthropic Claude key

  TIP: If you're not using Gemini or Anthropic yet, leave them blank.
       The gate will simply not use those providers.

── GATE ADMIN TOKENS ──
  KAIXU_ADMIN_TOKEN   = make up a long random string (this is your admin password)
                        Example: openssl rand -hex 32
  ADMIN_MASTER_TOKEN  = another long random string (master override token)
                        Can be the same as KAIXU_ADMIN_TOKEN for now, but
                        ideally use a different one for extra security.

  IMPORTANT: These tokens protect the /admin/* routes. Anyone with these can
  manage your AI budget, create app tokens, view usage, etc. Keep them secret.

── SKYE ERRORS ──
  SKYE_ERRORS_ADMIN_SECRET = another random string, used to authenticate error
                             reports coming from other platforms into the errors DB.

── EVERYTHING ELSE ──
  The other lines (feature flags, model names, brand name) already have good
  defaults in the example file. You don't need to change them to get started.

  DO NOT commit .dev.vars to git. It is already in .gitignore.

  IMPORTANT: This local file is for the gate itself. Downstream platforms do not
  copy provider keys out of this file. They only get the gate URL and their own
  app token.


STEP 3 — CREATE THE CLOUDFLARE DATABASES AND KV STORE
================================================================================

The gate needs three things created in Cloudflare before it can run:
  - Two D1 databases (SQLite databases hosted by Cloudflare)
  - One KV namespace (a key-value store for smoke test tracking)

--- Create the main AI database ---

  wrangler d1 create sky_currency

Cloudflare will print output like this:
  [[d1_databases]]
  binding = "DB"
  database_name = "sky_currency"
  database_id = "abc123..."   ← COPY THIS ID

Open wrangler.toml and find this section:
  [[d1_databases]]
  binding       = "DB"
  database_name = "sky_currency"
  database_id   = "REPLACE_AFTER_CREATE"

Replace REPLACE_AFTER_CREATE with the ID you just copied.

--- Create the errors database ---

  wrangler d1 create skye_errors_db

Same thing — copy the database_id and paste it into wrangler.toml:
  [[d1_databases]]
  binding       = "SKYE_ERRORS_DB"
  database_name = "skye_errors_db"
  database_id   = "REPLACE_AFTER_CREATE"   ← replace this one

--- Create the KV namespace ---

  wrangler kv namespace create KAIXU_SMOKE_KV

Copy the ID it gives you and paste into wrangler.toml:
  [[kv_namespaces]]
  binding = "KAIXU_SMOKE_KV"
  id      = "REPLACE_AFTER_CREATE"   ← replace this one

--- Create the R2 bucket (error log storage) ---

  wrangler r2 bucket create skye-errors-raw

This one doesn't need an ID pasted back — Wrangler finds it by bucket name.

After all of this, your wrangler.toml should have no more "REPLACE_AFTER_CREATE"
placeholders. They should all have real IDs in them.


STEP 4 — APPLY THE DATABASE SCHEMA
================================================================================

The databases exist now, but they're empty. You need to create the tables.
Run this for the main database:

  wrangler d1 execute sky_currency --remote --file=src/db/schema.sql

Run this for the errors database (if SkyErrors platform will connect to it):

  wrangler d1 execute skye_errors_db --remote --file=src/db/schema.sql

  NOTE: If skye_errors_db uses a different schema file, use that path instead.
  The main gate's schema.sql covers the sky_currency DB tables.


STEP 5 — SEED THE DATABASE WITH STARTER DATA
================================================================================

The schema creates empty tables. The seed file fills them with the starting
AI providers, model aliases, routing rules, and the first app wallet.

  wrangler d1 execute sky_currency --remote --file=src/db/seed.sql

What this seeds:
  - 3 AI providers: OpenAI, Gemini, Anthropic
  - Model aliases: kaixu/flash, kaixu/deep, kaixu/code, kaixu/vision, kaixu/embed
  - A starting wallet for SuperIDE with 50,000 SKYFUEL
  - Routing rules for each model alias
  - Pricing rates per alias

  WARNING: The seed.sql starts with DELETE statements that wipe the tables first.
  Only run this on a fresh database. If you've already seeded and added live app
  tokens, running seed.sql again will DELETE all your custom tokens and wallets.
  For production re-seeds, use the admin API routes instead.


STEP 6 — SET YOUR SECRETS IN CLOUDFLARE (for production)
================================================================================

The .dev.vars file only works when running locally. For the live deployed worker,
you set secrets through Wrangler. Run one command per secret:

  wrangler secret put OPENAI_API_KEY
  (Wrangler will prompt you to paste the value. Press enter. Done.)

  wrangler secret put OPENAI_TEXT_KEY
  wrangler secret put OPENAI_IMAGES_KEY
  wrangler secret put OPENAI_VIDEOS_KEY
  wrangler secret put OPENAI_AUDIO_KEY
  wrangler secret put OPENAI_REALTIME_KEY
  wrangler secret put GEMINI_API_KEY
  wrangler secret put ANTHROPIC_API_KEY
  wrangler secret put KAIXU_ADMIN_TOKEN
  wrangler secret put ADMIN_MASTER_TOKEN
  wrangler secret put SKYE_ERRORS_ADMIN_SECRET

  TIP: You can also set secrets in the Cloudflare dashboard under:
       Workers & Pages → 0megaskyegate → Settings → Environment Variables

  The non-secret config (APP_NAME, feature flags, model names, etc.) is already
  in wrangler.toml under [vars] so it deploys automatically — you don't need to
  set those manually.


STEP 6.5 — SET THE ONLY DOWNSTREAM AI VARS YOU SHOULD NEED
================================================================================

Once 0megaSkyeGate is deployed and you have issued app tokens, downstream apps
should be configured like this:

  Browser-first tools (Kaixu67, many SkaixuPro modules, SkyeMail browser helpers)
    OMEGA_GATE_URL=https://0megaskyegate.skyesoverlondon.workers.dev

  Netlify-backed apps (KaixuSuper-IDE, SkyeMail functions, other server callers)
    OMEGA_GATE_URL=https://0megaskyegate.skyesoverlondon.workers.dev
    KAIXU_APP_TOKEN=the app token you issued for that platform

  SuperIDE
    KAIXU_GATEWAY_ENDPOINT=https://0megaskyegate.skyesoverlondon.workers.dev
    KAIXU_APP_TOKEN=the app token you issued for SuperIDE

Do not set provider keys on these downstream apps. They call the gate.


STEP 7 — TEST IT LOCALLY FIRST
================================================================================

Before deploying to the world, run it on your own machine:

  npm run dev

This starts the worker locally at http://localhost:8787

Test the health check:
  curl http://localhost:8787/v1/health

You should see something like:
  {"status":"ok","gate":"0megaSkyeGate","env":"development"}

If you see that — the gate is running. If you see an error, check that your
.dev.vars file is filled in correctly.


STEP 8 — DEPLOY TO CLOUDFLARE
================================================================================

When you're ready to go live:

  npm run deploy

This runs wrangler deploy under the hood. Wrangler will:
  1. TypeScript-compile the source
  2. Bundle everything into a single Worker script
  3. Upload it to Cloudflare under the name "0megaskyegate"
  4. Print the live URL when done

The live URL will be:
  https://0megaskyegate.skyesoverlondon.workers.dev

Test the live gate immediately:
  curl https://0megaskyegate.skyesoverlondon.workers.dev/v1/health

You should see the same health response, now with "env":"production".


STEP 9 — VERIFY WITH A REAL AI CALL
================================================================================

To test that AI actually works through the gate, you need an app token.
The seed.sql already created one for SuperIDE. Get its raw token by checking
the seed file — the token_hash in the DB is a SHA-256 hash of the actual token.

For a quick smoke test without a real token, hit the smokehouse:
  https://0megaskyegate.skyesoverlondon.workers.dev/smokehouse

This runs an internal health check across all AI modalities and returns a report.
No token required.

For a real gated AI call with a token:
  curl -X POST https://0megaskyegate.skyesoverlondon.workers.dev/v1/chat \
    -H "Authorization: Bearer YOUR_APP_TOKEN" \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -d '{"model":"kaixu/flash","messages":[{"role":"user","content":"hello"}]}'

If you get a JSON response with a "choices" array — everything is working.


ISSUING NEW APP TOKENS
================================================================================

Every platform that talks to the gate needs its own app token.
You create them via the admin API. You need your KAIXU_ADMIN_TOKEN for this.

First, create a wallet for the new app:
  curl -X POST https://0megaskyegate.skyesoverlondon.workers.dev/admin/wallets \
    -H "Authorization: Bearer YOUR_ADMIN_TOKEN" \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -d '{"scope_type":"app","scope_id":"kaixu67","currency":"SKYFUEL","balance":25000}'

Then issue a token for that wallet:
  curl -X POST https://0megaskyegate.skyesoverlondon.workers.dev/admin/keys/issue \
    -H "Authorization: Bearer YOUR_ADMIN_TOKEN" \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -d '{
      "app_id": "kaixu67",
      "org_id": "org_skyes",
      "wallet_id": "THE_WALLET_ID_FROM_ABOVE",
      "allowed_aliases": ["kaixu/flash","kaixu/deep"],
      "rate_limit_rpm": 60
    }'

The response will include the raw token. Copy it immediately — it is only shown
once. Store it in the platform's Netlify env vars as KAIXU_APP_TOKEN.

If the platform is a browser-first surface, store only the gate URL client-side.
Do not expose KAIXU_APP_TOKEN in browser JavaScript unless that surface was
explicitly designed for public token use and locked down accordingly.


AUTOMATIC STUFF YOU DON'T HAVE TO SET UP
================================================================================

These happen automatically once the gate is deployed:

  - Cron job runs every 30 minutes (set in wrangler.toml) — runs smoke tests
    and cleans up old error logs older than 30 days.

  - Cloudflare Observability is enabled (wrangler.toml [observability]) — you can
    see request logs, error rates, and p99 latency in the Cloudflare dashboard
    under Workers & Pages → 0megaskyegate → Logs.

  - Fallback routing is enabled (ENABLE_FALLBACKS=true) — if your primary
    AI provider is down, the gate automatically retries with the next provider
    in the model alias list.


THE FLOW WHEN A PLATFORM CALLS THE GATE
================================================================================

Here's what happens every time Kaixu67, SuperIDE, or any other platform
sends a request to the gate. This is for your mental model:

  Platform sends:
    POST /v1/chat
    Authorization: Bearer sk_app_kaixu67_xxxxx
    Body: { "model": "kaixu/flash", "messages": [...] }

  Gate does:
    1. Extracts the Bearer token from the header
    2. SHA-256 hashes it and looks it up in the app_tokens DB table
    3. If not found or disabled → returns 401 Unauthorized
    4. Checks the wallet balance — does this app have enough SKYFUEL?
    5. If not enough → returns 402 Payment Required
    6. Looks up "kaixu/flash" in model_aliases → resolves to gemini-2.5-flash
       (or gpt-5.4-mini as fallback if Gemini is down)
    7. Sends the request to Gemini's API with your GEMINI_API_KEY
    8. Gets the response back
    9. Deducts SKYFUEL from the wallet
    10. Logs the usage event to the DB
    11. Returns the response to the platform


CURRENT TRUTH CHECK
================================================================================

As of this guide revision, the approved AI architecture is:

  - 0megaSkyeGate holds provider keys
  - downstream platforms point AI traffic at 0megaSkyeGate
  - downstream server apps authenticate with KAIXU_APP_TOKEN
  - Legacy direct browser persistence stacks are not part of the AI gateway contract

If you find a platform still wired directly to a legacy direct browser persistence stack or a legacy
brain for AI behavior, that platform is out of policy and needs migration.

  From the platform's perspective: they just got a normal OpenAI-style response.
  They never see the actual provider key. They never talk to Gemini directly.


TROUBLESHOOTING
================================================================================

Problem: "wrangler login" opens browser but nothing happens
Fix:     Try wrangler login --browser=false and follow the link manually

Problem: Deploy fails with "database_id not found"
Fix:     You forgot to replace REPLACE_AFTER_CREATE in wrangler.toml
         Run the d1 create commands from Step 3 and paste the IDs

Problem: /v1/health returns 500
Fix:     Your DB tables don't exist yet. Run the schema.sql step (Step 4)

Problem: AI calls return 401
Fix:     The app token you're using doesn't match what's in the DB.
         Either re-seed (if dev) or issue a fresh token via the admin API

Problem: AI calls return 402
Fix:     The wallet is out of SKYFUEL. Top it up:
         curl -X POST .../admin/wallets/{wallet_id}/credit \
           -H "Authorization: Bearer YOUR_ADMIN_TOKEN" \
           -d '{"amount":50000,"note":"top up"}'

Problem: AI calls return a real response but model is wrong
Fix:     Check the model_aliases table. The alias "kaixu/flash" may be pointing
         to a model your API key doesn't have access to. Check your OpenAI/Gemini
         plan limits.

Problem: Wrangler says "unknown binding" for DB or KAIXU_SMOKE_KV
Fix:     You created the D1/KV in Cloudflare but the wrangler.toml still has the
         REPLACE_AFTER_CREATE placeholder. Paste the real IDs in and redeploy.


QUICK REFERENCE — ALL COMMANDS IN ORDER
================================================================================

  npm install
  wrangler login
  cp .dev.vars.example .dev.vars        ← fill this in
  wrangler d1 create sky_currency       ← copy the ID into wrangler.toml
  wrangler d1 create skye_errors_db     ← copy the ID into wrangler.toml
  wrangler kv namespace create KAIXU_SMOKE_KV  ← copy ID into wrangler.toml
  wrangler r2 bucket create skye-errors-raw
  wrangler d1 execute sky_currency --remote --file=src/db/schema.sql
  wrangler d1 execute sky_currency --remote --file=src/db/seed.sql
  wrangler secret put OPENAI_API_KEY
  wrangler secret put KAIXU_ADMIN_TOKEN
  wrangler secret put ADMIN_MASTER_TOKEN
  wrangler secret put SKYE_ERRORS_ADMIN_SECRET
  (... other secrets as needed ...)
  npm run dev                           ← test locally at localhost:8787
  npm run deploy                        ← go live


WHAT'S IN THE FOLDER (FOR REFERENCE)
================================================================================

  src/index.ts              — entry point; handles all incoming Worker requests
  src/router.ts             — routes each URL path to the right handler
  src/auth/
    verifyAppToken.ts       — checks the Bearer token against the DB
    verifyAdminToken.ts     — checks the admin token
    policyGuard.ts          — enforces per-token allowed aliases + rate limits
  src/adapters/             — one file per modality (chat, stream, images, etc.)
    openaiChat.ts           — wraps the chat endpoint
    openaiStream.ts         — wraps the SSE streaming endpoint
    openaiImages.ts         — wraps image generation
    openaiVideos.ts         — wraps video generation (Sora)
    openaiAudioSpeech.ts    — wraps text-to-speech
    openaiAudioTranscriptions.ts — wraps speech-to-text
    openaiRealtime.ts       — wraps the realtime WebSocket API
  src/providers/
    openai.ts               — OpenAI API integration
    gemini.ts               — Gemini API integration
    anthropic.ts            — Anthropic API integration
    normalizeRequest.ts     — converts incoming request to provider format
    normalizeResponse.ts    — converts provider response back to standard format
  src/ledger/
    reserveBudget.ts        — puts a hold on SKYFUEL before the call
    debitWallet.ts          — subtracts SKYFUEL after call completes
    creditWallet.ts         — adds SKYFUEL to a wallet (admin top-up)
    finalizeUsage.ts        — writes usage event to DB
    refundUsage.ts          — refunds SKYFUEL if call failed
  src/db/
    schema.sql              — creates all DB tables
    seed.sql                — fills tables with starter data
    queries.ts              — reusable DB query functions
  src/utils/
    errors.ts               — error helpers and error pipeline integration
    hashing.ts              — SHA-256 token hashing
    ids.ts                  — ID generation (nanoid-style)
    sse.ts                  — server-sent events streaming helper
    trace.ts                — request tracing functions
  wrangler.toml             — Cloudflare deployment config (name, bindings, vars)
  .dev.vars.example         — template for your local secrets (copy → .dev.vars)
  tsconfig.json             — TypeScript config
  package.json              — npm scripts (dev, deploy, typecheck)

